[{"id":"55c483a9-3491-426a-9294-6a28fada6075","projectId":"d79d1bcd-5371-4f22-b8f4-c3ee39d17d28","documentId":"73dac391-c9b9-498a-a485-5e836c0228ee","type":"note","x":-585.111,"y":-664.889,"width":485.28,"height":199.822,"zIndex":5,"createdAt":1777544540775,"updatedAt":1777544567532,"data":{"type":"note","content":"<h3 class=\"text-text-100 mt-3 -mb-1 text-[1.125rem] font-bold\">Rest &amp; Motion</h3><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Rest</strong> — object doesn't change position w.r.t. surroundings.\n<strong>Motion</strong> — object changes position w.r.t. surroundings.</p><p>\n\n</p><blockquote class=\"ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300\">\n<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">⚠️ Both are <strong>relative</strong> — depend on the observer. A passenger in a train is at rest relative to co-passengers, but in motion relative to someone on the platform.</p></blockquote>","color":"#dbeafe","sourceExcerpt":"2.1.1 Rest and Motion","sourcePageNumber":2}},{"id":"56ec9426-384c-423c-9fe2-c515d37f7d33","projectId":"d79d1bcd-5371-4f22-b8f4-c3ee39d17d28","documentId":"73dac391-c9b9-498a-a485-5e836c0228ee","type":"note","x":-194.071,"y":460.056,"width":414.738,"height":355.698,"zIndex":24,"createdAt":1777544726485,"updatedAt":1777544753401,"data":{"type":"note","content":"<h3 class=\"text-text-100 mt-3 -mb-1 text-[1.125rem] font-bold\">Speed vs Velocity</h3><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Average Speed</strong> = Total Distance / Total Time <em>(scalar, always +ve)</em>\n<strong>Average Velocity</strong> = Displacement / Time <em>(vector, can be −ve or 0)</em></p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Special cases:</strong></p><ul class=\"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3\">\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Equal distances at speeds v₁ &amp; v₂ → avg speed = <strong>2v₁v₂ / (v₁+v₂)</strong> (harmonic mean)</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Equal times at speeds v₁ &amp; v₂ → avg speed = <strong>(v₁+v₂) / 2</strong> (arithmetic mean)</li>\n</ul><blockquote class=\"ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300\">\n<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Example:</strong> Car goes 120 km at 60 km/h, returns at 40 km/h → avg speed = 48 km/h, avg velocity = <strong>0</strong> (round trip)</p>\n</blockquote><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Instantaneous Velocity</strong> = dx/dt = slope of x-t graph at that point</p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><blockquote class=\"ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300\">\n<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Example:</strong> x = 3t² + 5t + 2 → v = dx/dt = 6t + 5 → at t=2s, <strong>v = 17 m/s</strong></p></blockquote>","color":"#dbeafe","sourceExcerpt":"2.3 Speed and Velocity","sourcePageNumber":5}},{"id":"667e675f-91b7-4dd5-93be-0e47257e04d4","projectId":"d79d1bcd-5371-4f22-b8f4-c3ee39d17d28","documentId":"73dac391-c9b9-498a-a485-5e836c0228ee","type":"note","x":-58.883,"y":957.339,"width":553.547,"height":277.191,"zIndex":30,"createdAt":1777544780965,"updatedAt":1777544791622,"data":{"type":"note","content":"<h3 class=\"text-text-100 mt-3 -mb-1 text-[1.125rem] font-bold\">Acceleration</h3><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Definition:</strong> Rate of change of velocity. Vector quantity — same direction as velocity means speeding up, opposite means slowing down.</p><ul class=\"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3\">\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Average: a = (v₂ − v₁) / (t₂ − t₁)</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Instantaneous: a = dv/dt = d²x/dt²</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Unit: <strong>m/s²</strong></li>\n</ul><blockquote class=\"ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300\">\n<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Example:</strong> v = 4t² − 2t + 3 → a = 8t − 2 → at t=3s, <strong>a = 22 m/s²</strong></p>\n</blockquote><p>\n\n\n\n</p><blockquote class=\"ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300\">\n<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">⚠️ <strong>Common misconception:</strong> Negative acceleration ≠ always slowing down! If velocity is also negative, the object is actually speeding up (both same direction).</p>\n</blockquote>","color":"#dbeafe","sourceExcerpt":"2.4 Acceleration","sourcePageNumber":6}},{"id":"68fb3927-21ac-496b-aa50-5a75e277e6a7","projectId":"d79d1bcd-5371-4f22-b8f4-c3ee39d17d28","documentId":"73dac391-c9b9-498a-a485-5e836c0228ee","type":"note","x":-193.1408125,"y":1375.7921875,"width":467.076,"height":364.8,"zIndex":37,"createdAt":1777544819290,"updatedAt":1777544841772,"data":{"type":"note","content":"<h3 class=\"text-text-100 mt-3 -mb-1 text-[1.125rem] font-bold\">&nbsp;Graph Interpretation</h3><div class=\"overflow-x-auto w-full px-2 mb-6\"><table class=\"min-w-full border-collapse text-sm leading-[1.7] whitespace-normal\"><thead class=\"text-left\"><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold\">Graph</th><th scope=\"col\" class=\"text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold\">Slope gives</th><th scope=\"col\" class=\"text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold\">Area gives</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">x-t</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Velocity</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">—</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">v-t</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Acceleration</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Displacement</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">a-t</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">—</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Change in velocity (Δv)</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>x-t graph clues:</strong></p><p>\n\n\n</p><ul class=\"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3\">\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Horizontal line → at rest</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Straight line → uniform velocity</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Curve → acceleration present</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Steeper slope → higher speed</li></ul>","color":"#dbeafe","sourceExcerpt":"2.5 Graphical Representation of Motion","sourcePageNumber":7}},{"id":"a3d5396f-93cd-4b7d-a7c8-bbbc2b76bd02","projectId":"d79d1bcd-5371-4f22-b8f4-c3ee39d17d28","documentId":"73dac391-c9b9-498a-a485-5e836c0228ee","type":"note","x":-296.027,"y":-349.849,"width":443.182,"height":171.378,"zIndex":11,"createdAt":1777544596403,"updatedAt":1777544613468,"data":{"type":"note","content":"<h3 class=\"text-text-100 mt-3 -mb-1 text-[1.125rem] font-bold\">Frame of Reference</h3><p>\n</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">A coordinate system + clock attached to an observer. In 1D motion, a single x-axis is enough — position is just one number, positive or negative based on which side of origin.</p>","color":"#dbeafe","sourceExcerpt":"2.1.2 Frame of Reference","sourcePageNumber":3}},{"id":"b800d2d3-98b9-4f26-add8-30e7be59eb45","projectId":"d79d1bcd-5371-4f22-b8f4-c3ee39d17d28","documentId":"73dac391-c9b9-498a-a485-5e836c0228ee","type":"note","x":-308.542,"y":-32.8522,"width":472.765,"height":336.355,"zIndex":17,"createdAt":1777544646374,"updatedAt":1777544666530,"data":{"type":"note","content":"<h3 class=\"text-text-100 mt-3 -mb-1 text-[1.125rem] font-bold\">Distance vs Displacement</h3><div class=\"overflow-x-auto w-full px-2 mb-6\"><table class=\"min-w-full border-collapse text-sm leading-[1.7] whitespace-normal\"><thead class=\"text-left\"><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold\">Property</th><th scope=\"col\" class=\"text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold\">Distance</th><th scope=\"col\" class=\"text-text-100 border-b-0.5 border-border-300/60 py-2 pr-4 align-top font-bold\">Displacement</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Type</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Scalar</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Vector</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Value</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Always ≥ 0</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Can be +, −, 0</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Depends on</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Entire path</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Only start &amp; end point</td></tr><tr><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">Round trip</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">&gt; 0</td><td class=\"border-b-0.5 border-border-300/30 py-2 pr-4 align-top\">= 0</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Formula:</strong> Δx = x_final − x_initial</p><p>\n\n\n</p><blockquote class=\"ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300\">\n<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Example:</strong> Walk 300 m east + 400 m north → Distance = 700 m, Displacement = √(300²+400²) = <strong>500 m</strong> (northeast)</p></blockquote>","color":"#dbeafe","sourceExcerpt":"2.2.1 Distance vs Displacement","sourcePageNumber":4}},{"id":"c5adb7bd-38fb-4820-a2d2-ac39a217e9d0","projectId":"d79d1bcd-5371-4f22-b8f4-c3ee39d17d28","documentId":"73dac391-c9b9-498a-a485-5e836c0228ee","type":"note","x":-208.4,"y":2570.67,"width":570.613,"height":389.831,"zIndex":46,"createdAt":1777544951051,"updatedAt":1777544966586,"data":{"type":"note","content":"<h3 class=\"text-text-100 mt-3 -mb-1 text-[1.125rem] font-bold\">Free Fall</h3><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">All objects fall with the same acceleration <strong>g ≈ 9.8 m/s²</strong> regardless of mass <em>(Galileo proved, Apollo 15 confirmed on Moon with hammer + feather)</em></p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Sign convention (upward = +ve):</strong></p><ul class=\"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3\">\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">v = u − gt</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">s = ut − ½gt²</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">v² = u² − 2gs</li>\n</ul><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Object thrown upward:</strong></p><ul class=\"[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3\">\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Max height H = u²/2g</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Time to top = u/g</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Total flight time = 2u/g</li>\n<li class=\"whitespace-normal break-words pl-2\">Speed on return = launch speed (same magnitude)</li>\n</ul><blockquote class=\"ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300\">\n<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><strong>Example:</strong> Ball thrown up at 25 m/s (g=10) → H = 31.25 m, time up = 2.5s, total time = <strong>5s</strong></p>\n</blockquote><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><blockquote class=\"ml-2 border-l-4 border-border-300/10 pl-4 text-text-300\">\n<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">⚠️ At highest point: <strong>v = 0 but a = g ≠ 0</strong> — this is a very common exam mistake!</p></blockquote>","color":"#dbeafe","sourceExcerpt":"2.7 Free Fall — Motion Under Gravity","sourcePageNumber":11}}]